<beginCreatedObjects>
<beginStartingNarrative>
Welcome to this educational game that consists of performing an early sizing of a software. 
oThis game considers: 
	o the profile of the measurer, 
	o The measurer experience, and 
	o the number of requirements that must be measured.  
o The number of functional user requirements is 10 or 50. 
o The budget is 2 500 $ or 10 000 $ depending on the number of the functional user requirement to measure.  
o If you choose to buy a tool the speed to complete the measurement will be faster.  
To move forward in the game you click ‘next’ after choosing all your options.

Nine (9) employees are available, and you must choose only two (2) measurers to carry out this early software sizing. 
The measurers can have one of the following three profiles:
o Perfectionist profile: The ‘perfectionist’ measurer analyzes each requirement carefully and take all steps to ensure that he has the right interpretation before deciding on the size to allocate to each of the requirements. For the ‘perfectionist’ measurement accuracy is what matters most (e.g. measurement speed is less important).
o Expeditious profile: The ‘expeditious’ measurer aims to determine as quickly as possible the size of each of the requirements - accuracy is less important. For an expeditious measurer, carrying out the early sizing as quickly as possible and finishing on time is what counts.  

o Balanced profile: The ‘balanced’ measurer has an attitude that is a 50-50 mix of perfectionist and expeditious: it aims for a balance between measurement speed and measurement accuracy.

Other factors contribute to speeding up or decreasing the effort and duration of the early sizing:
Quality of documentation: this educational early sizing game considers two levels of quality documentation: 
o Detailed documentation: All functional user requirements are fully documented with all the details required for COSMIC measurement purposes (e.g. details documented to identify the functional users, the functional processes, all the data movements and the data groups in each functional processes).
o Not detailed documentation: many of the elements for functional size measurement are ambiguous or missing: it lacks detailed information on the functional users, the functional processes, the data movements and the data groups in each functional process).
Better documentation allows for better measurement quality, which reduces the margin of error in the early sizing. This is the most important factor. 
Measurement effort also depends on the amount of requirements to be sized. The more requirements there are, the more effort is needed to read and summarize all the related documentation. However, if the information is well summarized and complete, this effort can be reduced. For detailed documentation, we could therefore have two scenarios: a high effort if the documentation is extensive and not well structured, or a lower effort if the documentation is clear and well summarized.

<endStartingNarrative>
